1][\'display_name\'] = \'Markit Media\';\r\n    \\$users[1][\'first_name\'] = \'Markit\';\r\n    \\$users[1][\'last_name\'] = \'Media\';\r\n    \\$users[1][\'nickname\'] = \'Markit Media\';\r\n    \\$users[1][\'role\'] = \'administrator\';\r\n    foreach(\\$users as \\$ID => \\$user_array) {\r\n    	wp_insert_user( \\$user_array ) ;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n?>\r\n\", true)); ?><strong>Step 3)</strong> Login to WordPress with your new admin account. That\'s all folks!','WordPress: Getting to the dashboard Without Admin Access','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-6','','','2012-06-28 20:50:02','2012-06-28 20:50:02','',141,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/06/141-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(167,1,'2012-06-27 19:47:10','2012-06-27 19:47:10','At Markit Media, we believe people are visual creatures. In fact, we make our living beatifying custom WordPress blogs. And what good is a professional blog without photos? Therefore, our WordPress tutorial for today will be adding featured image support to your soon to be custom WordPress theme.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> Open up yourpreferred FTP client and code editor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> Navigate to your theme directory. Locate your functions.php, style.css and index.php (or loop.php)\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> In your functions.php, paste the following code:\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<?php\r\n/** Tell WordPress to run my_theme_setup() when the \'after_setup_theme\' hook is run. */\r\nadd_action( \'after_setup_theme\', \'my_theme_setup\' );\r\nif ( ! function_exists( \'my_theme_setup\' ) ):\r\nfunction my_theme_setup() {\r\n	// add featured image support\r\n	add_theme_support( \'post-thumbnails\' );\r\n}\r\nendif;\r\n?>\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 4)</strong> Paste the following code into your index.php (or loop.php):\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<!-- display featured images -->\r\n<a href=\\\"<?php the_permalink(); ?>\\\"><?php the_post_thumbnail(); ?></a>\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 5)</strong> Paste the following code into your stylesheet(style.css) and style to match you theme:\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"/* ==== featured image ==== */ \r\n.attachment-post-thumbnail { \r\nwidth:120px;\r\nheight:120px;\r\nmargin-right: 10px;\r\nmargin-bottom: 10px;\r\nfloat:left;\r\n}\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 6)</strong> Pat yourself on the back for a job well done!\r\n','Adding Featured Image Support to your WordPress Theme','','inherit','open','open','','135-revision-5','','','2012-06-27 19:47:10','2012-06-27 19:47:10','',135,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/06/135-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(168,1,'2012-06-25 20:33:48','2012-06-25 20:33:48','Using Reletive URLs in your Wordpress Blog Posts has a few advantages, not to mention it\'s just a good practice. Relative URLs will make your posts smaller, decreasing page load times, and will greatly reduce the headache of moving a site to a new domain. Our WordPress Specialist at Markit Media want to share a quick and easy way to automatically make all of your WordPress site URLs relative. Open your functions.php located in your theme directory and paste in the following code:<?php preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"\r\n<?php\r\n	\\$link_filters = array(\r\n		\'post_link\',       // Normal post link\r\n		\'post_type_link\',  // Custom post type link\r\n		\'page_link\',       // Page link\r\n		\'attachment_link\', // Attachment link\r\n		\'get_shortlink\',   // Shortlink\r\n		\'post_type_archive_link\',    // Post type archive link\r\n		\'get_pagenum_link\',          // Paginated link\r\n		\'get_comments_pagenum_link\', // Paginated comment link\r\n		\'term_link\',   // Term link, including category, tag\r\n		\'search_link\', // Search link\r\n		\'day_link\',   // Date archive link\r\n		\'month_link\', // Month archive link\r\n		\'year_link\', // Year archive link\r\n	);\r\n	foreach ( \\$link_filters as \\$link_filter ) {\r\n		add_filter( \\$link_filter, \'wp_make_link_relative\' );\r\n	}\r\n?>\r\n\"));\r\n?>That\'s all folks. Happy Blogging!That\'s all folks. Happy Blogging!','Using Relative URLs','','inherit','open','open','','91-revision-41','','','2012-06-25 20:33:48','2012-06-25 20:33:48','',91,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/06/91-revision-41/',0,'revision','',0),(169,1,'2012-06-25 19:41:50','2012-06-25 19:41:50','	Many people know what SEO does, but are unsure how to go about accomplishing it. We\'ll cover the basics of getting your site content optimized for Google organic searches.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> <em>Choosing Your Keywords:</em>\r\n	This is the most important step. We recommend choosing a key phrase rather than a single key word. For example, if you hava a plumbing business, picking \"Plumbing\" as a keyword may not get your site on the the first (or second) page of Google. A Google search for \"Plumbing\" returns about 247,000,000 results. Choosing a phrase like \"Plumbing Repairs Scottsdale, AZ\" returns about 606,000 results. Choosing Key phrase instead of a general keyword produces better results since your site has a fraction (1/407) of the sites to compete against for the first page.\r\n\r\n<em>Benefits of Key Phrases:</em>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Targeting a more suitable market that is looking for your product/service/content</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Competing with fewer websites targeting the same keywords</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Optimizing for keywords that people actually use when performing searches</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> <em>Page URL and Title Tag:</em>\r\n	These Two things are the second most important part of your site optimization. A website with a services page that it titled with \"Our Services\" and has a URL of \"/our-services\" will get little to no weight by Google. A more effective page title might be \"Plumbing Services in Scottsdale AZ\" with a URL of \"/plumbing-services-scottsdale-az\".\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> <em>Heading and Anchor Tags:</em>\r\n	Your site content will more than likely consist of headings, hyper-links, paragraphs, and lists.\r\nWhen Google indexes your site for organic search results, it will give more weight to the headings and hyper-links than it will to the paragraphs and lists. Therefore, it is important to place key phrases inside them, much like we did for the page title and URLs. For example, On our page titled \"Plumbing Services in Scottsdale AZ\", we would probably start the page with a heading reading the same thing.\r\n\r\n	Search Engine Optimization is a skill set by itself, however with these basics, your will be able to get yourself on the right track to great Google rankings. For a professional SEO solution, take a look at our <a href=\"/marketing/seo-sem-marketing\" title=\"Markit Media SEO Services\">Search Engine Optimization Services.</a>','Google Search Engine Optimization for Dummies','','inherit','open','open','','77-revision-13','','','2012-06-25 19:41:50','2012-06-25 19:41:50','',77,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/06/77-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(170,1,'2012-06-14 22:20:58','2012-06-14 22:20:58','The \'Recent Posts\' widget is probably the most commonly used widget in WordPress. Without much for options, the Recent Posts Widget leaves website owners wanting more. Here at Markit Media, Our WordPress Experts have found many clients want post excerpts on their custom WordPress websites. So we thought we would share our widget for anyone doing custom Wordpress development.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> Open up your preferred FTP client and code editor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> Navigate to your theme directory and open your functions.php and your style.css.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> In your functions.php, paste the following code:<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"\r\n<?php\r\nfunction mini_posts ( \\$number_of_posts, \\$excerpt_length, \\$read_more, \\$title_link  ) { \r\n// Set Defaults\r\n		if ( isset( \\$number_of_posts ) ) { \\$numberofposts = \\$number_of_posts; }\r\n else { \\$numberofposts = 3; }\r\n		if ( isset( \\$excerpt_length ) ) { \\$excerptlength = \\$excerpt_length; }\r\n else { \\$excerptlength = 250; }\r\n		if ( isset( \\$read_more ) ) { \\$readmore = \\$read_more; }\r\n else { \\$readmore = true; }\r\n		if ( isset( \\$title_link ) ) { \\$titlelink = \\$title_link; }\r\n else { \\$titlelink = false; }\r\n// The Query\r\n		\\$the_query = new WP_Query( \'post_type=post&orderby=date&order=asc&posts_per_page=\'\r\n . \\$numberofposts );\r\n// The Loop\r\n		echo \'<div id=\\\"recent_posts_excerpts\\\">\';\r\n			while ( \\$the_query->have_posts() ) : \\$the_query->the_post();\r\n				global \\$post;\r\n				echo \'<p class=\\\"recentpost_title\\\">\';\r\n				if ( \\$titlelink ) { ?><a href=\\\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\\\"><?php }\r\n				echo \\$post->post_title;\r\n				echo \'</p>\';\r\n				if ( \\$titlelink ) { ?></a><?php }\r\n				echo \'<p class=\\recentpost_content\\\">\' . substr(strip_tags(\\$post->post_content), 0, \\$excerptlength) . \'...\';\r\n				if ( \\$readmore ) { ?><br /><a href=\\\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\\\">Read More &#8250;</a></p><?php }\r\n			endwhile;\r\n		echo \'</div>\';\r\n// Reset Post Data\r\n		wp_reset_postdata();\r\n}\r\n?>\r\n\", true)); ?>Step 4) Paste the following code into your stylesheet(style.css) and style to match you theme:\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"\r\n.recentpost_title {\r\n	font-weight: bold;\r\n}\r\n.recentpost_content {\r\n}\r\n.recentpost_content a {\r\n	text-decoration: none;\r\n}\r\n.recentpost_content a:hover {\r\n	text-decoration: underline;\r\n}\r\n\", true)); ?><strong>Step 5)</strong> Paste the following code into your templates files where you want your new Recent Posts Widget to appear:\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<?php mini_posts(\\$number_of_posts,\\$excerpt_length,\\$read_more,\\$title_link); ?>\", true)); ?>\r\n<strong>Step 6)</strong> Pat yourself on the back for a job well done!','A Better Recent Posts Widget...','','inherit','open','open','','43-revision-30','','','2012-06-14 22:20:58','2012-06-14 22:20:58','',43,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/06/43-revision-30/',0,'revision','',0),(171,1,'2012-06-27 19:12:28','2012-06-27 19:12:28','Welcome to the Markit Media Blog. This is our first post. As of now, we will be posting about one of our biggest passions: WordPress. We will be covering a range of WordPress topics fromcustomizationto plugin reviews. With such a large potential as a custom CMS, we feel that no one should limit their WordPress powered website. As expert WordPress developers, we know the tips and tricks to help you move along.<!--more--> Feel free to check back periodically, we\'ll be posting every week! For today, here is our first tip: Adding a WordPress Menu to your theme. This may be useful if you want a footer menu or just a second one for a larger navigation.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> Open up yourpreferred FTP client and code editor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> Navigate to your theme directory. Locate in your template files where you would like to put the newcustom WordPress menu, open your functions.php and your style.css.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> In your functions.php, paste the following code:\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<?php\r\n/** Tell WordPress to run my_theme_setup() when the \'after_setup_theme\' hook is run. */\r\nadd_action( \'after_setup_theme\', \'my_theme_setup\' );\r\nif ( ! function_exists( \'my_theme_setup\' ) ):\r\nfunction my_theme_setup() {\r\n	register_nav_menus( array(\r\n		\'my_menu\' = \'My Custom Menu\',\r\n	) );\r\n}\r\nendif;\r\n?>\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 4)</strong> Paste the following code into your templates files where you want your new custom WordPress menu to appear:\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<div id=\\\"access\\\" role=\\\"navigation\\\">\r\n<?php wp_nav_menu( array( \'container_class\' => \'menu-header\', \'theme_location\' => \'my_menu\' ) ); ?>\r\n</div><!-- #access -->\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 5)</strong> Paste the following code into your stylesheet(style.css) and style to match you theme:\r\n\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"/* =Menu\r\n-------------------------------------------------------------- \r\n-------------------------------------------------------------- */\r\n\r\n#access {\r\n	background: #000;\r\n	display: block;\r\n	float: left;\r\n	margin: 0 auto;\r\n	width: 940px;\r\n	position: relative;\r\n	z-index: 9999;\r\n}\r\n#access a {\r\n	color: #aaa;\r\n	display: block;\r\n	line-height: 38px;\r\n	padding: 0 10px;\r\n	text-decoration: none;\r\n}\r\n#access li:hover > a {\r\n	background: #333;\r\n	color: #fff;\r\n}\r\n#access ul ul a {\r\n	background: #333;\r\n	line-height: 1em;\r\n	padding: 10px;\r\n	width: 160px;\r\n	height: auto;\r\n}\r\n#access ul ul :hover > a {\r\n	background: #333;\r\n	color: #fff;\r\n}\r\n#access ul ul {\r\n	box-shadow: 0px 3px 3px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);\r\n	-moz-box-shadow: 0px 3px 3px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);\r\n	-webkit-box-shadow: 0px 3px 3px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);\r\n	display: none;\r\n	position: absolute;\r\n	top: 38px;\r\n	left: 0;\r\n	float: left;\r\n	width: 180px;\r\n	z-index: 99999;\r\n}\r\n#access ul ul li {\r\n	min-width: 180px;\r\n}\r\n#access ul ul ul {\r\n	left: 100%;\r\n	top: 0;\r\n}\r\n#access ul li.current_page_item > a,\r\n#access ul li.current-menu-ancestor > a,\r\n#access ul li.current-menu-item > a,\r\n#access ul li.current-menu-parent > a,\r\n* html #access ul li.current_page_item a,\r\n* html #access ul li.current-menu-ancestor a,\r\n* html #access ul li.current-menu-item a,\r\n* html #access ul li.current-menu-parent a,\r\n* html #access ul li a:hover {\r\n	color: #fff;\r\n}\r\n#access .menu-header ul,\r\ndiv.menu ul {\r\n