r\n&#91;embed width=\"123\" height=\"456\"&#93;<code>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nTDNLUzjkpg</code>&#91;/embed&#93;\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWordPress natively supprts video embeds from the following sites:\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>YouTube (only public videos and playlists - \"unlisted\" and \"private\" videos will not embed)</li>\r\n	<li>Vimeo</li>\r\n	<li>DailyMotion</li>\r\n	<li>blip.tv</li>\r\n	<li>Flickr (both videos and images)</li>\r\n	<li>Viddler</li>\r\n	<li>Hulu</li>\r\n	<li>Qik</li>\r\n	<li>Revision3</li>\r\n	<li>Scribd</li>\r\n	<li>Photobucket</li>\r\n	<li>PollDaddy</li>\r\n	<li>WordPress.tv (only VideoPress-type videos for the time being)</li>\r\n	<li>SmugMug (WordPress 3.0+)</li>\r\n	<li>FunnyOrDie.com (WordPress 3.0+)</li>\r\n	<li>Twitter (WordPress 3.4+)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','Posting Videos in WordPress: a Tutorial','','inherit','open','open','','217-revision-12','','','2012-07-20 16:45:30','2012-07-20 16:45:30','',217,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/217-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(231,1,'2012-07-13 17:30:00','2012-07-13 17:30:00','<p><strong>Image slider</strong> is a popular effect and often used in portfolio sites and blogs. Most of these sliders are created by Javascript. But with CSS3s strength, we can implement an <strong>image slider with only pure CSS3</strong>. This article will guide you to do that.</p>\r\n<h2>1. The HTML Markup</h2>\r\n<p>The HTML markup for image slider is so simple like this:</p>\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\'<div id=\"images\">\r\n    <img id=\"image1\" src=\"1.jpg\" />\r\n    <img id=\"image2\" src=\"2.jpg\" />\r\n    <img id=\"image3\" src=\"3.jpg\" />\r\n    <img id=\"image4\" src=\"4.jpg\" />\r\n    <img id=\"image5\" src=\"5.jpg\" />\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"slider\">\r\n    <a href=\"#image1\">1</a>\r\n    <a href=\"#image2\">2</a>\r\n    <a href=\"#image3\">3</a>\r\n    <a href=\"#image4\">4</a>\r\n    <a href=\"#image5\">5</a>\r\n</div>\', true)); ?>\r\n<p>We list all images in a div with <code>id=\"images\"</code> and the slide control in a div with <code>id=\"slider\"</code>. Each slide control button is an <code>a</code> tag with the target points to corresponding image.</p>\r\n<h2>2. Basic CSS</h2>\r\n<p>We will style the images and slide control with some basic CSS to make them beautiful:</p>\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\'#images {\r\n    width: 400px;\r\n    height: 250px;\r\n    overflow: hidden;\r\n    position: relative;\r\n    margin: 20px auto;\r\n}\r\n#images img {\r\n    width: 400px;\r\n    height: 250px;\r\n    position: absolute;\r\n    top: 0;\r\n    left: -400px;\r\n}\r\n#images img:first-child {\r\n    left: 0;\r\n}\r\n#slider a {\r\n    text-decoration: none;\r\n    background: #E3F1FA;\r\n    border: 1px solid #C6E4F2;\r\n    padding: 4px 6px;\r\n    color: #222;\r\n}\r\n#slider a:hover {\r\n    background: #C6E4F2;\r\n}\', true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<p>In this code, we specify fixed width and height for both <code>#images</code> element and its images. We also set the <code>position=\"relative\"</code> for <code>#images</code>, and <code>position=\"absolute\"</code> for all images as well as their left and top attribute. This will make all images are put in the same place, they overlay each other.</p>\r\n<p>Notice the <em>negative left</em> attribute. It is used to set the beginning position of images, i.e. out of the <code>#images</code> div. Why do we do that? Because we want images slide from left to right into the <code>#image</code> div box.</p>\r\n<p>But when we launch the script, the <code>#images</code> div box is completely empty. We don\'t want that, so we set <code>left:0</code> for first image to display it in the <code>#images</code> div box.</p>\r\n<h2>3. CSS3 Transition For Slider</h2>\r\n<p>To slide images with CSS3, we\'ll use the transition feature. The CSS3 transition has the following syntax:<br>\r\n	transition: transition-property transition-duration transition-timing-function transition-delay;</p>\r\n<p>In our case, we need to slide from left to right, so the <code>transition-property</code> is left, but we will add some effect with opacity for cooler effect, so we use <code>all</code> for <code>transition-property</code>. The <code>transition-timing-function</code> should be <code>linear</code>. The delay and duration can be anything, I choose <code>1s</code>.<br>\r\n	So, the CSS3 for slide effect will be:</p>\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\'#images img {\r\n    z-index: 1;\r\n    opacity: 0;\r\n    transition: all linear 1s;\r\n    -o-transition: all linear 1s;\r\n    -moz-transition: all linear 1s;\r\n    -webkit-transition: all linear 1s;\r\n}\r\n#images img:target {\r\n    left: 0;\r\n    z-index: 9;\r\n    opacity: 1;\r\n}\', true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we use the <code>:target</code> pseudo code to target the image when we click on the slide control button. When the image is targeted, we set its <code>left</code> attribute to 0 to make sure the image is displayed inside <code>#images</code> div box.</p>\r\n<p>In this code, there\'s one more thing needed to be noticed. That\'s the <code>z-index</code> attribute. Because we put all images in the same place, so, when we need to display the targeted image, we should make it overlay others by specifying a higher <code>z-index</code>.</p>\r\n<p>So, the complete CSS for the image slider is:</p>\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\'#images {\r\n    width: 400px;\r\n    height: 250px;\r\n    overflow: hidden;\r\n    position: relative;\r\n    margin: 20px auto;\r\n}\r\n#images img {\r\n    width: 400px;\r\n    height: 250px;\r\n    position: absolute;\r\n    top: 0;\r\n    left: -400px;\r\n    z-index: 1;\r\n    opacity: 0;\r\n    transition: all linear 500ms;\r\n    -o-transition: all linear 500ms;\r\n    -moz-transition: all linear 500ms;\r\n    -webkit-transition: all linear 500ms;\r\n}\r\n#images img:target {\r\n    left: 0;\r\n    z-index: 9;\r\n    opacity: 1;\r\n}\r\n#images img:first-child {\r\n    left: 0;\r\n}\r\n#slider a {\r\n    text-decoration: none;\r\n    background: #E3F1FA;\r\n    border: 1px solid #C6E4F2;\r\n    padding: 4px 6px;\r\n    color: #222;\r\n}\r\n#slider a:hover {\r\n    background: #C6E4F2;\r\n}\', true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<p>One disadvantage of this method that the first image is always displayed as a background. If you really don\'t want to have it, there\'s a solution: don\'t use CSS3 transition for left property (set <code>left:0</code> for original images), and use CSS3 transition for opacity only.</p>\r\n','Image Sliders with CSS','','inherit','open','open','','183-revision-9','','','2012-07-13 17:30:00','2012-07-13 17:30:00','',183,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/183-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(232,1,'2012-07-06 23:29:43','2012-07-06 23:29:43','Here at Markit media, our web developers love nothing more than creating beautiful websites. The only thing our developers love more, is a site with beautiful functionality. So for our lesson today, we\'ll be showing you how to create image rollovers without loading times or rollover delays. We will do this with a little css, and a clever image file.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> The first step is creating your image with the roll over state included. For example, let\'s say we wanted this image to change when we mouse over it:\r\n<img src=\"http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/roll.png\" alt=\"\" title=\"roll\" width=\"193\" height=\"62\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-149\" />\r\nWe would need to create the image with the normal state at the top of the image, and the hover state at the bottom, like so:\r\n<img src=\"http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/rollover.png\" alt=\"\" title=\"rollover\" width=\"193\" height=\"124\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-150\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> The next step is to write the HTML to include the image. Yours should look something like this:\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<div id=\\\"button\\\"></div>\", true)); ?>\r\nor\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"<a href=\\\"#\\\" id=\\\"button\\\">&nbsp;</a>\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> The final step is to write the CSS to roll the image over. It will look something like this:\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\"#button {\r\n	background-image: url(http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/rollover.png);\r\n	background-repeat: no-repeat;\r\n	background-position: top;\r\n	height: 62px;\r\n	width: 193px;\r\n}\r\n#button:hover {\r\n	background-position: bottom;\r\n}\", true)); ?>\r\n\r\nYour final result should look like this (mouse over to see hover state):\r\n\r\n<div id=\"button\"></div>','Better Image Rollovers with CSS','','inherit','open','open','','148-revision-12','','','2012-07-06 23:29:43','2012-07-06 23:29:43','',148,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/148-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(233,1,'2012-07-17 16:47:11','2012-07-17 16:47:11','What is Back-linking? Back-linking is the single most important part of off-page SEO that someone can do. Back-linking is process of creating links to your website from other websites. They can be a reciprocal or a one way link. The reason that this is important is that when a search engine rates a site\'s popularity, it does so by a measure of how many others sites link to it. The more sites that link to yours, or back-links, the higher your site will appear in search engine results organically. One great way to build back-links is to list your site with online business directories. You can also ask other sites to link to yours in exchange for returning the favor. Building back-links is a long slow process, so don\'t get discouraged. A few months of dedicated work will payoff. Most importantly, don\'t stop. Also, do avoid link farming. Companies will offer services to build back-links. Some are good while others will hurt your site ranking by spamming your links. Until next time, happy blogging!','Back-Linking: Just Do It!','','inherit','open','open','','209-revision-6','','','2012-07-17 16:47:11','2012-07-17 16:47:11','',209,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/209-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(234,1,'2012-07-16 17:18:44','2012-07-16 17:18:44','Last week we spoke about the potential of Google Maps as a marketing tool. As part 2 of our Google Maps posting, we\'ll be showing your how to get yourself listed on the maps and in search results. You can add a listing by going to <a href=\"http://www.google.com/local/add/g?hl=en-US&gl=US#phonelookup\" title=\"Add a Business to Google Maps\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.google.com/local/add/g?hl=en-US&gl=US#phonelookup</a>. Go ahead and enter your business phone number to be sure that there isn\'t a listing for your business yet. Once you\'ve done that start entering your business details. It is important to be a thorough a possible. In particular, be sure to list your phone number, website, listing description, and listing categories. The description is probably the single most important part. This is where most people get lazy and where you will gain a edge on your competition. When writing your description, try to include keywords that people will type when looking for services or products that you offer. This will almost guarantee you top results. Once you\'ve have your listing as complete as possible, we recommend opting for a phone verification since it will get you on the maps and in search results the fastest! That\'s it, you are now on your way to great search rankings with Google Maps.','Adding A Google Maps Business Listing','','inherit','open','open','','205-revision-4','','','2012-07-16 17:18:44','2012-07-16 17:18:44','',205,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/205-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(235,1,'2012-07-13 17:32:14','2012-07-13 17:32:14','Many people looking to market their business via the internet often overlook the power of Google Maps. They become too focused on Adwords and quickly exhaust their budget with little to show for it! About 90% of Google searches result in a click in the organic results and the remaining 10% click through an Adword result. When making a location relevant search such as \"Fine Dining near Scottsdale AZ\", a map result is almost always shown. Most people who do enter their business into the Google Maps Directory do not put more than their name and address. With just a little extra effort and a few keys words, it\'s easy to dominate the map results. What does this mean? Just 10 minutes of SEO will get your business at the top of a Google search driving traffic to your site or business! In our next blog post, we\'ll shown you how to make the most of your Google Maps submission! Until then, happy blogging!','Google Maps: An Undiscovered Gem!','','inherit','open','open','','192-revision-7','','','2012-07-13 17:32:14','2012-07-13 17:32:14','',192,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/192-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(236,1,'2012-07-09 23:38:46','2012-07-09 23:38:46','Snippets are the text appearing under each result in a Google / Yahoo / Bing search. They\'re meant to give the user an idea of what\'s contained in each results. If a search engine understands the content of your site, it can create a rich snippet to display in search results. For example, a restaurant with rich snippets could appear in search results with a price range of their entrees and user ratings of their food. This helps users to recognize your site as relevant to their search, encouraging more clicks to your site. You can help search engines to find this relevant information by adding HTML markup to your content thus creating a rich snippet. Some example of different types of snippets include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Applications</li>\r\n	<li>Addresses</li>\r\n	<li>Authors</li>\r\n	<li>Events</li>\r\n	<li>Music</li>\r\n	<li>People</li>\r\n	<li>Products</li>\r\n	<li>Products with many offers</li>\r\n	<li>Recipes</li>\r\n	<li>Reviews</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nThe following is an example a address as a rich snippet:\r\n<?php echo preg_replace(\'%\\r%\', \'\', highlight_string(\'<div id=\"hcard-Markit-Media-Group-LLC\" class=\"vcard\">\r\n    <div class=\"adr\">\r\n        <div class=\"fn\">Markit Media Group LLC.</div>\r\n        <div class=\"street-address\">4419 N. Scottsdale Rd. #118</div>\r\n        <span class=\"locality\">Scottsdale</span>,\r\n        <span class=\"region\">AZ</span>,\r\n        <span class=\"postal-code\">85251</span>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <div class=\"tel\">Phone: (480) 245-4287</div>\r\n    Fax: (480) 292-9477<br />\r\n    <a href=\"/contact-us/\" class=\"address vcard_contact_links\">Map and Directions </a><br />\r\n    <a href=\"/contact-us/\" class=\"address vcard_contact_links\">E-mail Us</a>\r\n</div>\', true)); ?>\r\n\r\nFor more information about rich snippets check out these resources on google.com:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://support.google.com/webmasters/bin/answer.py?hl=en&answer=99170&topic=1088472&ctx=topic\" title=\"About rich Snippets\" target=\"_blank\">About rich Snippets</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/richsnippets?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.urbanspoon.com%2Fr%2F23%2F1600592%2Frestaurant%2FPoint-Breeze%2FAlma-Pan-Latin-Kitchen-Pittsburgh\" title=\"Rich Snippets Testing Tool\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Snippets Testing Tool</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Better SEO with Rich Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-7','','','2012-07-09 23:38:46','2012-07-09 23:38:46','',175,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/175-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(237,1,'2012-07-06 23:30:43','2012-07-06 23:30:43','As Wordpress bloggers, we at the Markit Media Dev team always have one thing on our minds: Search Engine Optimization. And when we think about SEO, we are interested in how we display in organic search results, simply getting there isn\'t good enough. We want to the most enticing result on google, otherwise we\'ll just be glanced over. For this reason, we often find ourselves using the <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wordpress-seo/\" title=\"The WordPress SEO plugin Homepage\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress SEO plugin by Yoast</a>, and here\'s why:\r\n\r\n<em>Write Better Content:</em> WordPress SEO forces you to choose a keyword or phrase to focus on as you write your content. This helps to get you the most relevant content possible. Good content is Key.\r\n\r\n<em>Preview your Snippets:</em> My favorite pieace of functionalty, the snippet preview! This will show you exactly how your site will look in Google / Yahoo / Bing search results. One thing that I like to do as a marketing firm is to include my phone number in snippets. A potenial client can give me a call without even having to click on any organic search results. Need I say more?\r\n\r\n<em>Technical WordPress Search Engine Optimization:</em> While out of the box WordPress is pretty good for SEO, it needs some tweaks here and there. The WordPress SEO plugin guides you through some of the settings needed, for instance by reminding you to enable pretty permalinks. But it also goes beyond that, by automatically optimizing and inserting the meta tags and link elements that Google and other search engines like so much. \r\n\r\n<em>Import Meta Info:</em> Lastly, WordPress SEO allows you to Import your meta info from other popular SEO plugins like All In One SEO Pack or HeadSpace2.\r\n\r\nI hope you\'ve enjoyed this review of WordPress SEO, happy blogging!','Plugin Review: WordPress SEO','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-5','','','2012-07-06 23:30:43','2012-07-06 23:30:43','',162,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/162-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(238,1,'2012-07-06 23:29:43','2012-07-06 23:29:43','	Many people know what SEO does, but are unsure how to go about accomplishing it. We\'ll cover the basics of getting your site content optimized for Google organic searches.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 1)</strong> <em>Choosing Your Keywords:</em>\r\n	This is the most important step. We recommend choosing a key phrase rather than a single key word. For example, if you hava a plumbing business, picking \"Plumbing\" as a keyword may not get your site on the the first (or second) page of Google. A Google search for \"Plumbing\" returns about 247,000,000 results. Choosing a phrase like \"Plumbing Repairs Scottsdale, AZ\" returns about 606,000 results. Choosing Key phrase instead of a general keyword produces better results since your site has a fraction (1/407) of the sites to compete against for the first page.\r\n\r\n<em>Benefits of Key Phrases:</em>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Targeting a more suitable market that is looking for your product/service/content</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Competing with fewer websites targeting the same keywords</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Optimizing for keywords that people actually use when performing searches</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 2)</strong> <em>Page URL and Title Tag:</em>\r\n	These Two things are the second most important part of your site optimization. A website with a services page that it titled with \"Our Services\" and has a URL of \"/our-services\" will get little to no weight by Google. A more effective page title might be \"Plumbing Services in Scottsdale AZ\" with a URL of \"/plumbing-services-scottsdale-az\".\r\n\r\n<strong>Step 3)</strong> <em>Heading and Anchor Tags:</em>\r\n	Your site content will more than likely consist of headings, hyper-links, paragraphs, and lists.\r\nWhen Google indexes your site for organic search results, it will give more weight to the headings and hyper-links than it will to the paragraphs and lists. Therefore, it is important to place key phrases inside them, much like we did for the page title and URLs. For example, On our page titled \"Plumbing Services in Scottsdale AZ\", we would probably start the page with a heading reading the same thing.\r\n\r\n	Search Engine Optimization is a skill set by itself, however with these basics, your will be able to get yourself on the right track to great Google rankings. For a professional SEO solution, take a look at our <a href=\"/marketing/seo-sem-marketing\" title=\"Markit Media SEO Services\">Search Engine Optimization Services.</a>','Google Search Engine Optimization for Dummies','','inherit','open','open','','77-revision-14','','','2012-07-06 23:29:43','2012-07-06 23:29:43','',77,'http://www.markitmedia.com/blog/2012/07/77-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(239,1,'2012-07-20 16:46:26','2012-07-20 16:46:26','Today I would like to discuss WordPress native support for embeddding a video in post, or in layman\'s terms, posting a video. WordPress comes stock with the ability to recognize a link form many popular video site and use to to automatically embed a player in your post. (Check the \"Auto-embeds\" check box in Administration > Settings > Media SubPanel.)\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Check out this cool video:\r\n\r\n<code>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nTDNLUzjkpg</code>\r\n\r\nThat was a cool video.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nOptionally you can wrap your video link in an &#91;embed&#93; shortcode. Using this shortcode does the same thing, but doesn\'t require the link to be on it\'s own line, and allows you to specify the maximum (but not fixed) size of the video like so:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n&#91;embed width=\"123\" height=\"456\"&#93;<code>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nTDNLUzjkpg</code>&#91;/embed&#93;\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWordPress natively supprts video embeds from the following sites:\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>YouTube (only public videos and playlists - \"unlisted\" and \"private\" videos will not embed)</li>\r\n	<li>Vimeo</li>\r\n	<li>DailyMotion</li>\r\n	<li>blip.tv</li>\r\n	<li>Flickr (both videos and images)</li>\r\n	<li>Viddler</li>\r\n	<li>Hulu</li>\r\n	<li>Qik</li>\r\n	<li>Revision3</li